# Git commits and pull requests

**Never commit, push, or open a PR without explicit user permission.** Propose first; execute only after approval.

## Commits

Prefer **granular** commits — one logical change per commit. Split when changes span unrelated concerns (e.g. logging setup vs docs vs CI).

If a single commit would bundle too much, **stop and propose** a commit plan instead of committing:

```
1. docs: add repository URL to README and pyproject urls
2. feat: bootstrap logging from pyproject.toml via logging518
3. chore: rename benchmark flags and make bench target
```

Ask which commits to run (all, subset, or one squashed).

### Message format

Short **type** prefix + brief summary. Optional body with bullet details when helpful.

```
docs: add repository URL to README and project urls

- Replace clone placeholder with github.com/Pawlo77/nlp-shap
- Add Homepage, Repository, Issues, Documentation to pyproject.toml
```

**Types:** `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `test`, `refactor`, `chore`, `ci`, `build`, `perf`

- Subject: imperative, lowercase type, no period, ~72 chars
- Body: what changed and why — not a file list unless useful
- One concern per commit; do not mix unrelated types

### Before committing

1. Run `make check`, `make docs`, and `make notebooks` (when `examples/*.ipynb` changed)
2. Run `git status`, `git diff`, `git log -5` (parallel)
3. Draft message(s) matching the split plan
4. Stage only files for that commit; commit; verify with `git status`

Do not `--no-verify`, amend, or force-push unless user rules explicitly allow.

### Before pushing

- Confirm `make check` is green on the commits being pushed
- Example notebooks must include **executed outputs** (run `make notebooks` first)

### After pushing

- Watch remote workflows until all succeed: `gh run watch --exit-status`
- If **Prek Checks** or other required workflows fail, fix on a follow-up commit — do not leave `main` red

## Pull requests

Same permission gate — **propose title and body; create only when asked.**

**Title:** same style as commit subject — `feat: add connector benchmark harness`

**Body:**

```markdown
## Summary
- Bullet: user-facing or architectural outcome

## Test plan
- [ ] make check
- [ ] …
```

Keep PRs focused. Large work → suggest stacked commits or multiple PRs. Use `gh pr create` with HEREDOC body when user approves.
